    "summary": "The Numidian Kingdoms (c. 300–46 BC) were Berber kingdoms in North Africa (modern Algeria) that played a crucial role in the [[event:1052|Punic Wars]] and the [[event:1090|Jugurthine War]] — initially as Rome's allies whose cavalry proved decisive at the [[event:1057|Battle of Zama]], later as a source of the corruption and military challenge that exposed Rome's republican weaknesses.\n\nNumidia comprised two main kingdoms — the Massaesyli in the west under Syphax, and the Massyli in the east under [[event:1162|Masinissa of Numidia]] — which were bitter rivals. During the Second Punic War, Syphax allied with Carthage while Masinissa (after changing sides) allied with Rome and contributed devastating cavalry at the [[event:1057|Battle of Zama]]. Rome rewarded Masinissa by unifying Numidia under his rule, and he built it into a prosperous agricultural kingdom. His successors quarreled over succession; one of them, Jugurtha, who seized power by murdering rivals, triggered the [[event:1090|Jugurthine War]] — during which his reported bribery of Roman senators shocked public opinion and fueled the populist politics that launched [[event:1069|Marian Reforms]]'s Marius's career. Julius Caesar finally ended Numidian independence in 46 BC, creating the Roman province of Africa Nova.",
